04863nam a22005895i 9780804784689DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047846897 a10.1515/97808047846892doi  a(DE-B1597)563684  a(OCoLC)1198930907  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD6276.E18bG56 2013 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a320.5109522300aGlobal Futures in East Asia :bYouth, Nation, and the New Economy in Uncertain Times /cAnn Anagnost, Andrea Arai, Hai Ren. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Issues in Asia and the Pacific00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Life-Making in Neoliberal Times -- t1. The Middle-Class Norm and Responsible Consumption in China's Risk Society -- t2. Miraculous Rebirth: Making Global Places in Taiwan -- t3. On the Streets of Beijing: Medical Melodrama in the Everyday -- t4. On their Own: Becoming Cosmopolitan Subjects beyond College in South Korea -- t5. Smile Chaoyang: Education and Culture in Neoliberal Taiwan -- t6. "What If Your Client/Employer Treats Her Dog Better Than She Treats You?": Market Militarism and Market Humanism in Postsocialist Beijing -- t7. Notes to the Heart: New Lessons in National Sentiment and Sacrifice from Recessionary Japan -- t8. Neoliberal Speech Acts: The Equal Opportunity Law and Projects of the Self in a Japanese Corporate Office -- t9. Workplace Dramas and Labor Fantasies in 1990s Japan -- t10. Governmental Entanglements: The Ambiguities of Progressive Politics in Neoliberal Reform in South Korea -- tReferences Cited -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe East Asian economic miracle of the twentieth century is now a fond memory. What does it mean to be living in post-miracle times? For the youth of China, Taiwan, Japan, and South Korea, the opportunities and challenges of the neoliberal age, deeply shaped by global forces in labor markets, powerfully frame their life prospects in ways that are barely recognizable to their parents. Global Futures in East Asia gathers together ethnographic explorations of what its contributors call projects of "life-making." Here we see youth striving to understand themselves, their place in society, and their career opportunities in the nation, region, and world. While some express optimism, it is clear that many others dread their prospects in the competitive global system in which the failure to thrive is isolating, humiliating, and possibly even fatal. Deeply engaged with some of the most significant theoretical debates in the social sciences in recent years, and rich with rare cross-national comparisons, this collection will be of great interest to all scholars and students interested in the formation of subjects and subjectivities under globalization and neoliberalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEthnologyzEast AsiavCase studies. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspectszEast AsiavCase studies. 0aNeoliberalismzEast AsiavCase studies. 0aYouthxEmploymentzEast AsiavCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAnagnost, Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArai, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRen, Hai, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478468940uh